# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pseudonymization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:pseudonymization/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The **General Data Protection Regulation** (Regulation (EU) 2016/679), abbreviated **GDPR**, is a European Union regulation on information privacy in the European Union (EU) and the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR is an important component of EU privacy law and human rights law, in particular Article 8(1) of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It also governs the transfer of personal data outside the EU and EEA.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR's goals are to enhance individuals' control and rights over their personal information and to simplify the regulations for international business.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It supersedes the Data Protection Directive 95/46/EC and, among other things, simplifies the terminology.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The European Parliament and Council of the European Union adopted the GDPR on 14 April 2016, to become effective on 25 May 2018.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an EU regulation (instead of a directive), the GDPR has direct legal effect and does not require transposition into national law.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] However, it also provides flexibility for individual member states to modify (derogate from) some of its provisions.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an example of the Brussels effect, the regulation became a model for many other laws around the world, including in Brazil, Japan, Singapore, South Africa, South Korea, Sri Lanka, and Thailand.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] After leaving the European Union, the United Kingdom enacted its "UK GDPR", identical to the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), adopted on 28 June 2018, has many similarities with the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR also contains 173 recitals purposed to clarify scope and rationale for the regulatory provisions, as well as its legislative intents – Recital 4, for instance, begins by saying that the processing of personal data should be "designed to serve mankind".
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies if the data controller, or processor, or the data subject (person) is based in the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation also applies to organisations based outside the EU if they collect or process personal data of individuals located inside the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation does not apply to the processing of data by private persons provided that the purpose has no connection to a professional or commercial activity." (Recital 18).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] According to the European Commission, "Personal data is information that relates to an identified or identifiable individual.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If you cannot directly identify an individual from that information, then you need to consider whether the individual is still identifiable.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The data protection reform package also includes a separate Data Protection Directive for the police and criminal justice sector that provides rules on personal data exchanges at State level, Union level, and international levels.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A single set of rules applies to all EU member states.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Each member state establishes an independent supervisory authority (SA) to hear and investigate complaints, sanction administrative offences, etc.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] SAs in each member state co-operate with other SAs, providing mutual assistance and organising joint operations.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If a business has multiple establishments in the EU, it must have a single SA as its "lead authority", based on the location of its "main establishment" where the main processing activities take place.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The lead authority thus acts as a "one-stop shop" to supervise all the processing activities of that business throughout the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A European Data Protection Board (EDPB) co-ordinates the SAs.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] EDPB thus replaces the **Article 29** Data Protection Working Party.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are exceptions for data processed in an employment context or in national security that still might be subject to individual country regulations.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If informed *consent* is used as the lawful basis for processing, consent must have been explicit for data collected and each purpose data is used for.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent must be a specific, freely given, plainly worded, and unambiguous affirmation given by the data subject; an online form which has consent options structured as an opt-out selected by default is a violation of the GDPR, as the consent is not unambiguously affirmed by the user.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, multiple types of processing may not be "bundled" together into a single affirmation prompt, as this is not specific to each use of data, and the individual permissions are not freely given.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects must be allowed to withdraw this consent at any time, and the process of doing so must not be harder than it was to opt in.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data controller may not refuse service to users who decline consent to processing that is not strictly necessary in order to use the service.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent for children, defined in the regulation as being less than 16 years old (although with the option for member states to individually make it as low as 13 years old), must be given by the child's parent or custodian, and verifiable.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If consent to processing was already provided under the Data Protection Directive, a data controller does not have to re-obtain consent if the processing is documented and obtained in compliance with the GDPR's requirements (Recital 171).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right of access (**Article 15**) is a data subject right.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It gives people the right to access their personal data and information about how this personal data is being processed.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data subject must be able to transfer personal data from one electronic processing system to and into another, without being prevented from doing so by the data controller.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data that has been sufficiently anonymised is excluded, but data that has been only de-identified but remains possible to link to the individual in question, such as by providing the relevant identifier, is not.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Both data being 'provided' by the data subject and data being 'observed', such as about behaviour, are included.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, the data must be provided by the controller in a structured and commonly used standard electronic format.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right to data portability is provided by **Article 20**.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in the version of the GDPR that was adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are some instances where this objection does not apply.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A task being carried out for public interest.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] GDPR is also clear that the data controller must inform individuals of their right to object from the first communication the controller has with them.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This should be clear and separate from any other information the controller is providing and give them their options for how best to object to the processing of their data.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are instances the controller can refuse a request, in the circumstances that the objection request is "manifestly unfounded" or "excessive", so each case of objection must be looked at individually.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other countries such as Canada are also, following the GDPR, considering legislation to regulate automated decision making under privacy laws, even though there are policy questions as to whether this is the best way to regulate AI.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In the judgment *Österreichische Post* (C-300/21) the Court of Justice of the European Union gave an interpretation of the right to compensation.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 82(1) GDPR requires for the award of damages *(i)* an infringement of the GDPR, *(ii)* (actual) damage suffered and *(iii)* a causal link between the infringement and the damage suffered.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is not necessary that the damage suffered reaches a certain degree of seriousness.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is no European defined concept of damage.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Compensation is determined nationally in accordance with national law.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data processors are only liable for damage caused by processing in breach of obligations specifically imposed on processors by the GDPR, or for damage caused by processing which is outside, or contrary to, the lawful instructions of the data controller.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must clearly disclose any data collection, declare the lawful basis and purpose for data processing, and state how long data is being retained and if it is being shared with any third parties or outside of the EEA.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms have the obligation to protect data of employees and consumers to the degree where only the necessary data is extracted with minimum interference with data privacy from employees, consumers, or third parties.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms should have internal controls and regulations for various departments such as audit, internal controls, and operations.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects have the right to request a portable copy of the data collected by a controller in a common format, as well as the right to have their data erased under certain circumstances.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Public authorities, and businesses whose core activities consist of regular or systematic processing of personal data, are required to employ a *data protection officer* (DPO), who is responsible for managing compliance with the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must report data breaches to national supervisory authorities within 72 hours if they have an adverse effect on user privacy.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In some cases, violators of the GDPR may be fined up to €20 million or up to 4% of the annual worldwide turnover of the preceding financial year in case of an enterprise, whichever is greater.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] To be able to demonstrate compliance with the GDPR, the data controller must implement measures that meet the principles of data protection by design and by default.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] **Article 25** requires data protection measures to be designed into the development of business processes for products and services.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such measures include pseudonymising personal data, by the controller, as soon as possible (Recital 78).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is the responsibility and the liability of the data controller to implement effective measures and be able to demonstrate the compliance of processing activities even if the processing is carried out by a data processor on behalf of the controller (Recital 74).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As such, the data subject must also be provided with contact details for the data controller and their designated data protection officer, where applicable.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data protection impact assessments (**Article 35**) have to be conducted when specific risks occur to the rights and freedoms of data subjects.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Risk assessment and mitigation is required and prior approval of the data protection authorities is required for high risks.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A report by the European Union Agency for Network and Information Security elaborates on what needs to be done to achieve privacy and data protection by default.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It specifies that encryption and decryption operations must be carried out locally, not by remote service, because both keys and data must remain in the power of the data owner if any privacy is to be achieved.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The report specifies that outsourced data storage on remote clouds is practical and relatively safe if only the data owner, not the cloud service, holds the decryption keys.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] An example is encryption, which renders the original data unintelligible in a process that cannot be reversed without access to the correct decryption key.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR requires for the additional information (such as the decryption key) to be kept separately from the pseudonymised data.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Another example of pseudonymisation is tokenisation, which is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] While the tokens have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value, they allow for specific data to be fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Tokenisation does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This also requires much fewer computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Pseudonymisation is a privacy-enhancing technology and is recommended to reduce the risks to the concerned data subjects and also to help controllers and processors to meet their data protection obligations (Recital 28).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such requirements may be modified by each EU country.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The records shall be in electronic form and the controller or the processor and, where applicable, the controller's or the processor's representative, shall make the record available to the supervisory authority on request.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Controllers and processors of personal data must put in place *appropriate technical and organizational measures* to implement the data protection principles.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Business processes that handle personal data must be designed and built with consideration of the principles and provide safeguards to protect data (for example, using pseudonymization or full anonymization where appropriate).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must design information systems with privacy in mind.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] For instance, using the highest-possible privacy settings by default, so that the datasets are not publicly available by default and cannot be used to identify a subject.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] No personal data may be processed unless this processing is done under one of the six lawful bases specified by the regulation (consent, contract, public task, vital interest, legitimate interest or legal requirement).
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] When the processing is based on consent the data subject has the right to revoke it at any time.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A designated DPO can be a current member of staff of a controller or processor, or the role can be outsourced to an external person or agency through a service contract.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In any case, the processing body must make sure that there is no conflict of interest in other roles or interests that a DPO may hold.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The contact details for the DPO must be published by the processing organisation (for example, in a privacy notice) and registered with the supervisory authority.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO is similar to a compliance officer and is also expected to be proficient at managing IT processes, data security (including dealing with cyberattacks) and other critical business continuity issues associated with the holding and processing of personal and sensitive data.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The skill set required stretches beyond understanding legal compliance with data protection laws and regulations.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO must maintain a living data inventory of all data collected and stored on behalf of the organization.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] More details on the function and the role of data protection officer were given on 13 December 2016 (revised 5 April 2017) in a guideline document.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Organisations based outside the EU must also appoint an EU-based person as a representative and point of contact for their GDPR obligations.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This is a distinct role from a DPO, although there is overlap in responsibilities that suggest that this role can also be held by the designated DPO.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 42 and 43 of the GDPR set the legal basis for formal GDPR certifications.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] 42 GDPR, the purpose of this certification is to demonstrate “compliance with the GDPR of processing operations by controllers and processors”.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR certification also contributes to reduce the legal and financial risks of applicants, as well as of data controllers using certified data processing services.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The adoption of the European Data Protection Seals is under the responsibility of the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) and is recognized across all EU and EEA Member States.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In October 2022, the Europrivacy certification criteria were officially recognized by the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) to serve as European Data Protection Seal.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Europrivacy was developed by the European research programme and is managed by the European Centre for Certification and Privacy (ECCP) in Luxembourg.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] These are some cases which are not addressed in the GDPR specifically, thus are treated as exemptions.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Conversely, an entity or more precisely an "enterprise" has to be engaged in "economic activity" to be covered by the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Economic activity is defined broadly under European Union competition law.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies regardless of where the processing takes place.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This has been interpreted as intentionally giving GDPR extraterritorial jurisdiction for non-EU establishments if they are doing business with people located in the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is questionable whether the EU or its member states will in practice be able to enforce GDPR against organisations which have no establishment in the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under **Article 27**, non-EU establishments subject to GDPR are obliged to have a designee within the European Union, an "EU Representative", to serve as a point of contact for their obligations under the regulation.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The EU Representative is the Controller's or Processor's contact person vis-à-vis European privacy supervisors and data subjects, in all matters relating to processing, to ensure compliance with this GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A natural (individual) or legal (corporation) person can play the role of an EU Representative.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The non-EU establishment must issue a duly signed document (letter of accreditation) designating a given individual or company as its EU Representative.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The said designation can only be given in writing.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The intentional or negligent (willful blindness) character of the infringement (failure to designate an EU Representative) may rather constitute aggravating factors.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Non-EU public authorities and bodies are equally exempted.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Binding corporate rules, standard contractual clauses for data protection issued by a Data Processing Agreement (DPA), or a scheme of binding and enforceable commitments by the data controller or processor situated in a third country, are among examples.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The applicability of GDPR in the United Kingdom is affected by Brexit.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Although the United Kingdom formally withdrew from the European Union on 31 January 2020, it remained subject to EU law, including GDPR, until the end of the transition period on 31 December 2020.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, existing and relevant EU law was transposed into UK law upon completion of the transition, and the GDPR was amended by statutory instrument to remove certain provisions no longer needed due to the UK's non-membership in the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Thereafter, the regulation is referred to as "UK GDPR".
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The UK does not restrict the transfer of personal data to countries within the EEA under UK GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As part of the withdrawal agreement, the European Commission committed to perform an adequacy assessment.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 28 June 2021, the Commission confirmed the adequacy of the UK GDPR for four years; This was set to expire on 27 June 2025, but was extended for six months to give the Commission time to assess the impact of the Data (Use and Access) Act 2025.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 19 December 2025 the Commission renewed the 2021 adequacy decision until 27 December 2031.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In March 2021, Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Oliver Dowden stated that the UK was exploring divergence from the EU GDPR in order to "[focus] more on the outcomes that we want to have and less on the burdens of the rules imposed on individual businesses".
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As per a study conducted by Deloitte in 2018, 92% of companies believe they are able to comply with GDPR in their business practices in the long run.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Companies operating outside of the EU have invested heavily to align their business practices with GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The area of GDPR consent has a number of implications for businesses who record calls as a matter of practice.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A typical disclaimer is not considered sufficient to gain assumed consent to record calls.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Additionally, when recording has commenced, should the caller withdraw their consent, then the agent receiving the call must be able to stop a previously started recording and ensure the recording does not get stored.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] IT professionals expect that compliance with the GDPR will require additional investment overall: over 80 percent of those surveyed expected GDPR-related spending to be at least US$100,000.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It has been argued that smaller businesses and startup companies might not have the financial resources to adequately comply with the GDPR, unlike the larger international technology firms (such as Facebook and Google) that the regulation is ostensibly meant to target first and foremost.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A lack of knowledge and understanding of the regulations has also been a concern in the lead-up to its adoption.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A counter-argument to this has been that companies were made aware of these changes two years prior to them coming into effect and should have had enough time to prepare.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulations, including whether an enterprise must have a data protection officer, have been criticized for potential administrative burden and unclear compliance requirements.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is also concern regarding the implementation of the GDPR in blockchain systems, as the transparent and fixed record of blockchain transactions contradicts the very nature of the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Many media outlets have commented on the introduction of a "right to explanation" of algorithmic decisions, but legal scholars have since argued that the existence of such a right is highly unclear without judicial tests and is limited at best.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR has garnered support from businesses who regard it as an opportunity to improve their data management.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Mark Zuckerberg has also called it a "very positive step for the Internet", and has called for GDPR-style laws to be adopted in the US.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consumer rights groups such as The European Consumer Organisation are among the most vocal proponents of the legislation.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other supporters have attributed its passage to the whistleblower Edward Snowden.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Free software advocate Richard Stallman has praised some aspects of the GDPR but called for additional safeguards to prevent technology companies from "manufacturing consent".
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Academic experts who participated in the formulation of the GDPR wrote that the law "is the most consequential regulatory development in information policy in a generation.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Despite having had at least two years to prepare and do so, many companies and websites changed their privacy policies and features worldwide directly prior to GDPR's implementation, and customarily provided email and other notifications discussing these changes.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Phishing scams also emerged using falsified versions of GDPR-related emails, and it was also argued that some GDPR notice emails may have actually been sent in violation of anti-spam laws.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2019, a provider of compliance software found that many websites operated by EU member state governments contained embedded tracking from ad technology providers.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A blog, *GDPR Hall of Shame*, was also created to showcase unusual delivery of GDPR notices, and attempts at compliance that contained egregious violations of the regulation's requirements.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Its author remarked that the regulation "has a lot of nitty gritty, in-the-weeds details, but not a lot of information about how to comply", but also acknowledged that businesses had two years to comply, making some of its responses unjustified.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Research indicates that approximately 25% of software vulnerabilities have GDPR implications.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Since Article 33 emphasizes breaches, not bugs, security experts advise companies to invest in processes and capabilities to identify vulnerabilities before they can be exploited, including coordinated vulnerability disclosure processes.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of Android apps' privacy policies, data access capabilities, and data access behaviour has shown that numerous apps display a somewhat privacy-friendlier behaviour since the GDPR was implemented, although they still retain most of their data access privileges in their code.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of the Norwegian Consumer Council into the post-GDPR data subject dashboards on social media platforms (such as Google dashboard) has concluded that large social media firms deploy deceptive tactics in order to discourage their customers from sharpening their privacy settings.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Some companies, such as Klout, and several online video games, ceased operations entirely to coincide with its implementation, citing the GDPR as a burden on their continued operations, especially due to the business model of the former.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The volume of online behavioural advertising placements in Europe fell 25–40% on 25 May 2018.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Facebook and subsidiaries WhatsApp and Instagram, as well as Google LLC (targeting Android), were immediately sued by Max Schrems's non-profit NOYB just hours after midnight on 25 May 2018, for their use of "forced consent".
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Schrems asserts that both companies violated Article 7(4) by not presenting opt-ins for data processing consent on an individualized basis, and requiring users to consent to all data processing activities (including those not strictly necessary) or would be forbidden from using the services.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 21 January 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French DPA for showing insufficient control, consent, and transparency over use of personal data for behavioural advertising.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2018, following a journalistic investigation into Liviu Dragnea, the Romanian DPA (ANSPDCP) used a GDPR request to demand information on the RISE Project's sources.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In July 2019, the British Information Commissioner's Office issued an intention to fine British Airways a record £183 million (1.5% of turnover) for poor security arrangements that enabled a 2018 web skimming attack affecting around 380,000 transactions.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] British Airways was ultimately fined a reduced amount of £20m, with the ICO noting that they had "considered both representations from BA and the economic impact of COVID-19 on their business before setting a final penalty".
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics interviewed by *Politico* also argued that enforcement was also being hampered by varying interpretations between member states, the prioritisation of guidance over enforcement by some authorities, and a lack of cooperation between member states.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2021, Irish Council for Civil Liberties lodged a formal complaint of the Commission that it is in breach of its obligation under EU Law to carefully monitor how Ireland applies the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Until January 2023, the Commission published a new commitment based on the complaint of ICCL.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] While companies are now subject to legal obligations, there are still various inconsistencies in the practical and technical implementation of GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, according to the GDPR's right to access, the companies are obliged to provide data subjects with the data they gather about them.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, in a study on loyalty cards in Germany, companies did not provide the data subjects with the exact information of the purchased articles.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] One might argue that such companies do not collect the information of the purchased articles, which does not conform with their business models.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Therefore, data subjects tend to see that as a GDPR violation.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As a result, studies have suggested for a better control through authorities.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] According to the GDPR, end-users' consent should be valid, freely given, specific, informed and active.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, the lack of enforceability regarding obtaining lawful consents has been a challenge.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, a 2020 study, showed that the Big Tech, i.e.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft (GAFAM), use dark patterns in their consent obtaining mechanisms, which raises doubts regarding the lawfulness of the acquired consent.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2021, EU member states led by France were reported to be attempting to modify the impact of the privacy regulation in Europe by exempting national security agencies.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] After around 160 million Euros in GDPR fines were imposed in 2020, the figure was already over one billion Euros in 2021.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In 2024 and early 2025, GDPR enforcement actions intensified.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Irish Data Protection Commission (DPC) imposed a €345 million fine on TikTok for violations related to children's data privacy and insufficient safeguards for young users.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In January 2025, Meta was fined €1.2 billion for unlawful data transfers between the EU and the US, marking one of the largest GDPR fines to date.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 12 February 2025, the European Commission abandoned proposed regulations on technology patents, AI liability, and privacy for messaging apps due to strong lobbying and a lack of consensus among EU lawmakers, with major tech firms opposing the changes.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Mass adoption of these new privacy standards by multinational companies has been cited as an example of the "Brussels effect", a phenomenon wherein European laws and regulations are used as a baseline due to their gravitas.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The U.S. state of California passed the California Consumer Privacy Act on 28 June 2018, taking effect on 1 January 2020; it grants rights to transparency and control over the collection of personal information by companies in a similar means to GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics have argued that such laws need to be implemented at the federal level to be effective, as a collection of state-level laws would have varying standards that would complicate compliance.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Two other U.S. states have since enacted similar legislation: Virginia passed the Consumer Data Privacy Act on 2 March 2021, and Colorado enacted the Colorado Privacy Act on 8 July 2021.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Republic of Turkey, a candidate for European Union membership, adopted the Law on The Protection of Personal Data on 24 March 2016 in compliance with the EU acquis.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] China's 2021 Personal Information Protection Law is the country's first comprehensive law on personal data rights and is modelled after the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Switzerland will also adopt a new data protection law that largely follows EU's GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The CLOUD Act, enacted in 2018, is seen by the European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) as a law in possible conflict with the GDPR.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A 2024 study found that GDPR reduced both EU user website page views and website revenue by 12%.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The EU Digital Single Market strategy relates to "digital economy" activities related to businesses and people in the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As part of the strategy, the GDPR and the NIS Directive all apply from 25 May 2018.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The proposed ePrivacy Regulation was also planned to be applicable from 25 May 2018, but will be delayed for several months.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The eIDAS Regulation is also part of the strategy.
[src:pseudonymization/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In an initial assessment, the European Council has stated that the GDPR should be considered "a prerequisite for the development of future digital policy initiatives".
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:pseudonymization/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A **pseudonym** (/ˈsjuːdənɪm/; from Ancient Greek ψευδώνυμος*(*pseudṓnumos*)* 'falsely named') or **alias** (/ˈeɪli.əs/) is a fictitious name that a person assumes for a particular purpose, which differs from their original or true name (orthonym).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] This also differs from a new name that entirely or legally replaces an individual's own.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Many pseudonym holders use them because they wish to remain anonymous and maintain privacy, though this may be difficult to achieve as a result of legal issues.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonyms include stage names, user names, ring names, pen names, aliases, superhero or villain identities and code names, gamertags, and regnal names of emperors, popes, and other monarchs.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In some cases, it may also include nicknames.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Historically, they have sometimes taken the form of anagrams, Graecisms, and Latinisations.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonyms are different from new names that replace old ones.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Actors, musicians, and other performers sometimes use stage names for a degree of privacy, to better market themselves, and other reasons.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some pseudonyms are part of a cultural or organisational tradition; for example, devotional names are used by members of some religious institutes, and "cadre names" are used by Communist party leaders such as Trotsky and Lenin.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A *collective name* or *collective pseudonym* is one shared by two or more persons, for example, the co-authors of a work, such as Carolyn Keene, Erin Hunter, Ellery Queen, H.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Bustos Domecq, Nicolas Bourbaki, or James S.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Sometimes people change their names in such a manner that the new name becomes permanent and is used by all who know the person.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] This is not an alias or pseudonym, but in fact a new name.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In many countries, including common law countries, a name change can be ratified by a court and become a person's new legal name.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonymous authors may still have their various identities linked together through stylometric analysis of their writing style.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The precise degree of this unmasking ability and its ultimate potential is uncertain, but the privacy risks are expected to grow with improved analytic techniques and text corpora.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Authors may practice adversarial stylometry to resist such identification.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Businesspersons of ethnic minorities in some parts of the world are sometimes advised by an employer to use a pseudonym that is common or acceptable in that area when conducting business, to overcome racial or religious bias.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Criminals may use aliases, fictitious business names, and dummy corporations (corporate shells) to hide their identity, or to impersonate other persons or entities in order to commit fraud.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Aliases and fictitious business names used for dummy corporations may become so complex that, in the words of *The Washington Post*, "getting to the truth requires a walk down a bizarre labyrinth" and multiple government agencies may become involved to uncover the truth.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Giving a false name to a law enforcement officer is a crime in many jurisdictions.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A pen name is a pseudonym (sometimes a particular form of the real name) adopted by an author (or on the author's behalf by their publishers).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] English usage also includes the French-language phrase *nom de plume* (which in French literally means "pen name").
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The concept of pseudonymity has a long history.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In ancient literature it was common to write in the name of a famous person, not for concealment or with any intention of deceit; in the New Testament, the second letter of Peter is probably such.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A more modern example is all of *The Federalist Papers*, which were signed by Publius, a pseudonym representing the trio of James Madison, Alexander Hamilton, and John Jay.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The papers were written partially in response to several Anti-Federalist Papers, also written under pseudonyms.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] As a result of this pseudonymity, historians know that the papers were written by Madison, Hamilton, and Jay, but have not been able to discern with certainty which of the three authored a few of the papers.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] There are also examples of modern politicians and high-ranking bureaucrats writing under pseudonyms.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some female authors have used male pen names, in particular in the 19th century, when writing was a highly male-dominated profession.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The Brontë sisters used pen names for their early work, so as not to reveal their gender (see below) and so that local residents would not suspect that the books related to people of their neighbourhood.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Anne Brontë's *The Tenant of Wildfell Hall* (1848) was published under the name Acton Bell, while Charlotte Brontë used the name Currer Bell for *Jane Eyre* (1847) and *Shirley* (1849), and Emily Brontë adopted Ellis Bell as cover for *Wuthering Heights* (1847).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Other examples from the nineteenth-century are novelist Mary Ann Evans (George Eliot) and French writer Amandine Aurore Lucile Dupin (George Sand).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonyms may also be used due to cultural or organization or political prejudices.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Similarly, some 20th- and 21st-century male romance novelists – a field dominated by women – have used female pen names.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A few examples are Brindle Chase, Peter O'Donnell (as Madeline Brent), Christopher Wood (as Penny Sutton and Rosie Dixon), and Hugh C.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A pen name may be used if a writer's real name is likely to be confused with the name of another writer or notable individual, or if the real name is deemed unsuitable.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Authors who write both fiction and non-fiction, or in different genres, may use different pen names to avoid confusing their readers.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] For example, the romance writer Nora Roberts writes mystery novels under the name J.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In some cases, an author may become better known by their pen name, rather than their real name.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some famous examples of that include Samuel Clemens, writing as Mark Twain, Theodor Geisel, better known as Dr.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Seuss, and Eric Arthur Blair (George Orwell).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The British mathematician Charles Dodgson wrote fantasy novels as Lewis Carroll and mathematical treatises under his own name.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some authors, such as Harold Robbins, use several literary pseudonyms.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some pen names have been used for long periods, even decades, without the author's true identity being discovered, as with Elena Ferrante and Torsten Krol.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Joanne Rowling published the *Harry Potter* series as J.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Rowling also published the Cormoran Strike series of detective novels including *The Cuckoo's Calling* under the pseudonym Robert Galbraith.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Churchill (from his full surname Spencer Churchill which he did not otherwise use) in an attempt to avoid confusion with an American novelist of the same name.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The attempt was not wholly successful – the two are still sometimes confused by booksellers.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A pen name may be used specifically to hide the identity of the author, as with exposé books about espionage or crime, or explicit erotic fiction.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Erwin von Busse used a pseudonym when he published short stories about sexually charged encounters between men in Germany in 1920.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some prolific authors adopt a pseudonym to disguise the extent of their published output, e. g.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Stephen King writing as Richard Bachman.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Co-authors may choose to publish under a collective pseudonym, e. g., P.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Frederic Dannay and Manfred Lee used the name Ellery Queen as a pen name for their collaborative works and as the name of their main character.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Asa Earl Carter, a Southern white segregationist affiliated with the KKK, wrote Western books under a fictional Cherokee persona to imply legitimacy and conceal his history.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A famous case in French literature was Romain Gary.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Already a well-known writer, he started publishing books as Émile Ajar to test whether his new books would be well received on their own merits, without the aid of his established reputation.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] They were: Émile Ajar, like Romain Gary before him, was awarded the prestigious Prix Goncourt by a jury unaware that they were the same person.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Similarly, TV actor Ronnie Barker submitted comedy material under the name Gerald Wiley.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A collective pseudonym may represent an entire publishing house, or any contributor to a long-running series, especially with juvenile literature.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Examples include Watty Piper, Victor Appleton, Erin Hunter, and Kamiru M.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Another use of a pseudonym in literature is to present a story as being written by the fictional characters in the story.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The series of novels known as *A Series of Unfortunate Events* are written by Daniel Handler under the pen name of Lemony Snicket, a character in the series.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] This applies also to some of the several 18th-century English and American writers who used the name Fidelia.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] An **anonymity pseudonym** or multiple-use name is a name used by many different people to protect anonymity.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] It is a strategy that has been adopted by many unconnected radical groups and by cultural groups, where the construct of personal identity has been criticised.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] This has led to the idea of the "open pop star", such as Monty Cantsin.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonyms and acronyms are often employed in medical research to protect subjects' identities through a process known as de-identification.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Nicolaus Copernicus put forward his theory of heliocentrism in the manuscript *Commentariolus* anonymously, in part because of his employment as a law clerk for a church-government organization.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Sophie Germain and William Sealy Gosset used pseudonyms to publish their work in the field of mathematics – Germain, to avoid rampant 19th century academic misogyny, and Gosset, to avoid revealing brewing practices of his employer, the Guinness Brewery.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Satoshi Nakamoto is a pseudonym of a still unknown author or authors' group behind a white paper about bitcoin.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] While taking part in military activities, such as fighting in a war, the pseudonym might be known as a nom de guerre.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] It is chosen by the person involved in the activity.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Individuals using a computer online may adopt or be required to use a form of pseudonym known as a "handle" (a term deriving from CB slang), "user name", "login name", "avatar", or, sometimes, "screen name", "gamertag", "IGN (**I**n **G**ame (**N**ick)**N**ame)" or "nickname".
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] On the Internet, pseudonymous remailers use cryptography that achieves persistent pseudonymity, so that two-way communication can be achieved, and reputations can be established, without linking physical identities to their respective pseudonyms.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Aliasing is the use of multiple names for the same data location.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] More sophisticated cryptographic systems, such as anonymous digital credentials, enable users to communicate pseudonymously (*i.e.*, by identifying themselves by means of pseudonyms).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In well-defined abuse cases, a designated authority may be able to revoke the pseudonyms and reveal the individuals' real identity.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Use of pseudonyms is common among professional eSports players, despite the fact that many professional games are played on LAN.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonymity has become an important phenomenon on the Internet and other computer networks.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] For example, true anonymous remailer enables Internet users to establish unlinkable pseudonyms; those that employ non-public pseudonyms (such as the now-defunct Penet remailer) are called pseudonymous remailers.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The continuum of unlinkability can also be seen, in part, on Wikipedia.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some registered users make no attempt to disguise their real identities (for example, by placing their real name on their user page).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Until November 4, 2025, the pseudonym of unregistered users is their IP address, which can, in many cases, easily be linked to them.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] As a result, after the date in question, temporary accounts were invented and implemented on English Wikipedia.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Other registered users prefer to remain anonymous, and do not disclose identifying information.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] However, in certain cases, Wikipedia's privacy policy permits system administrators to consult the server logs to determine the IP address, and perhaps the true name, of a registered user.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] It is possible, in theory, to create an unlinkable Wikipedia pseudonym by using an Open proxy, a web server that disguises the user's IP address.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] But most open proxy addresses are blocked indefinitely due to their frequent use by vandals.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Additionally, Wikipedia's public record of a user's interest areas, writing style, and argumentative positions may still establish an identifiable pattern.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] System operators (sysops) at sites offering pseudonymity, such as Wikipedia, are not likely to build unlinkability into their systems, as this would render them unable to obtain information about abusive users quickly enough to stop vandalism and other undesirable behaviors.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Law enforcement personnel, fearing an avalanche of illegal behavior, are equally unenthusiastic.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Their views are supported by laws in some nations (such as Canada) that guarantee citizens a right to speak using a pseudonym.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] This right does not, however, give citizens the right to demand publication of pseudonymous speech on equipment they do not own.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Most websites that offer pseudonymity retain information about users.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] These sites are often susceptible to unauthorized intrusions into their non-public database systems.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] For example, in 2000, a Welsh teenager obtained information about more than 26,000 credit card accounts, including that of Bill Gates.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In 2003, VISA and MasterCard announced that intruders obtained information about 5.6 million credit cards.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Sites that offer pseudonymity are also vulnerable to confidentiality breaches.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In a study of a Web dating service and a pseudonymous remailer, University of Cambridge researchers discovered that the systems used by these Web sites to protect user data could be easily compromised, even if the pseudonymous channel is protected by strong encryption.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Typically, the protected pseudonymous channel exists within a broader framework in which multiple vulnerabilities exist.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonym users should bear in mind that, given the current state of Web security engineering, their true names may be revealed at any time.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonymity is an important component of the reputation systems found in online auction services (such as eBay), discussion sites (such as Slashdot), and collaborative knowledge development sites (such as Wikipedia).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A pseudonymous user who has acquired a favorable reputation gains the trust of other users.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] When users believe that they will be rewarded by acquiring a favorable reputation, they are more likely to behave in accordance with the site's policies.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Whitewashing is one specific form of a Sybil attack on distributed systems.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The social cost of cheaply discarded pseudonyms is that experienced users lose confidence in new users, and may subject new users to abuse until they establish a good reputation.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] System operators may need to remind experienced users that most newcomers are well-intentioned (see, for example, Wikipedia's policy about biting newcomers).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Concerns have also been expressed about sock puppets exhausting the supply of easily remembered usernames.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In addition a recent research paper demonstrated that people behave in a potentially more aggressive manner when using pseudonyms/nicknames (due to the online disinhibition effect) as opposed to being completely anonymous.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Researchers at the University of Cambridge showed that pseudonymous comments tended to be more substantive and engaged with other users in explanations, justifications, and chains of argument, and less likely to use insults, than either fully anonymous or real name comments.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Proposals have been made to raise the costs of obtaining new identities, such as by charging a small fee or requiring e-mail confirmation.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Others point out that Wikipedia's success is attributable in large measure to its nearly non-existent initial participation costs.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] People seeking privacy often use pseudonyms to make appointments and reservations.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Those writing to advice columns in newspapers and magazines may use pseudonyms.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] When used by an actor, musician, radio disc jockey, model, or other performer or "show business" personality a pseudonym is called a *stage name*, or, occasionally, a *professional name*, or *screen name*.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Members of a marginalized ethnic or religious group have often adopted stage names, typically changing their surname or entire name to mask their original background.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Stage names are also used to create a more marketable name, as in the case of Creighton Tull Chaney, who adopted the pseudonym Lon Chaney Jr., a reference to his famous father Lon Chaney.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Chris Curtis of Deep Purple fame was christened as Christopher Crummey ("crummy" is UK slang for poor quality).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In this and similar cases a stage name is adopted simply to avoid an unfortunate pun.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonyms are also used to comply with the rules of performing-arts guilds (Screen Actors Guild (SAG), Writers Guild of America, East (WGA), AFTRA, etc.), which do not allow performers to use an existing name, in order to avoid confusion.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] For example, these rules required film and television actor Michael Fox to add a middle initial and become Michael J.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Fox, to avoid being confused with another actor named Michael Fox.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The film-making team of Joel and Ethan Coen, for instance, share credit for editing under the alias Roderick Jaynes.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some stage names are used to conceal a person's identity, such as the pseudonym Alan Smithee, which was used by directors in the Directors Guild of America (DGA) to remove their name from a film they feel was edited or modified beyond their artistic satisfaction.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In theatre, the pseudonyms George or Georgina Spelvin, and Walter Plinge are used to hide the identity of a performer, usually when he or she is "doubling" (playing more than one role in the same play).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] David Agnew was a name used by the BBC to conceal the identity of a scriptwriter, such as for the Doctor Who serial *City of Death*, which had three writers, including Douglas Adams, who was at the time of writing, the show's script editor.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In another Doctor Who serial, *The Brain of Morbius*, writer Terrance Dicks demanded the removal of his name from the credits saying it could go out under a "bland pseudonym".
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pornographic actors regularly use stage names.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Sometimes these are referred to as *nom de porn* (like with *nom de plume*, this is English-language users creating a French-language phrase to use in English).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Having acted in pornographic films can be a serious detriment to finding another career.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Musicians and singers can use pseudonyms to allow artists to collaborate with artists on other labels while avoiding the need to gain permission from their own labels, such as the artist Jerry Samuels, who made songs under Napoleon XIV.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Rock singer-guitarist George Harrison, for example, played guitar on Cream's song "Badge" using a pseudonym.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In classical music, some record companies issued recordings under a *nom de disque* in the 1950s and 1960s to avoid paying royalties.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A number of popular budget LPs of piano music were released under the pseudonym Paul Procopolis.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Another example is that Paul McCartney used his fictional name "Bernerd Webb" for Peter and Gordon's song Woman.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Pseudonyms are used as stage names in heavy metal bands, such as Tracii Guns in LA Guns, Axl Rose and Slash in Guns N' Roses, Mick Mars in Mötley Crüe, Dimebag Darrell in Pantera, or C.C.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Some such names have additional meanings, like that of Brian Hugh Warner, more commonly known as Marilyn Manson: Marilyn coming from Marilyn Monroe and Manson from convicted serial killer Charles Manson.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Jacoby Shaddix of Papa Roach went under the name "Coby Dick" during the *Infest* era.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] He changed back to his birth name when *lovehatetragedy* was released.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] David Johansen, frontman for the hard rock band New York Dolls, recorded and performed pop and lounge music under the pseudonym Buster Poindexter in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The music video for Poindexter's debut single, Hot Hot Hot, opens with a monologue from Johansen where he notes his time with the New York Dolls and explains his desire to create more sophisticated music.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Ross Bagdasarian Sr., creator of Alvin and the Chipmunks, wrote original songs, arranged, and produced the records under his real name, but performed on them as David Seville.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Danish pop pianist Bent Fabric, whose full name is Bent Fabricius-Bjerre, wrote his biggest instrumental hit "Alley Cat" as Frank Bjorn.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] For a time, the musician Prince used an unpronounceable "Love Symbol" as a pseudonym ("Prince" is his actual first name rather than a stage name).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] He wrote the song "Sugar Walls" for Sheena Easton as "Alexander Nevermind" and "Manic Monday" for the Bangles as "Christopher Tracy".
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] (He also produced albums early in his career as "Jamie Starr").
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Many Italian-American singers have used stage names, as their birth names were difficult to pronounce or considered too ethnic for American tastes.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In 2009, the British rock band Feeder briefly changed their name to Renegades so they could play a whole show featuring a set list in which 95 per cent of the songs played were from their forthcoming new album of the same name, with none of their singles included.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Frontman Grant Nicholas felt that if they played as Feeder, there would be an uproar over him not playing any of the singles, so he used the pseudonym as a hint.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] A series of small shows were played in 2010, at 250 to 1,000-capacity venues, with the plan to not say who the band really was, and to just announce the shows as if they were a new band.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In many cases, hip-hop and rap artists prefer to use pseudonyms that represents some variation of their name, personality, or interests.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Examples include Iggy Azalea (her stage name is a combination of her dog's name, Iggy, and her home street in Mullumbimby, Azalea Street), Ol' Dirty Bastard (known under at least six aliases), Diddy (previously known at various times as Puffy, P.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Diddy, and Puff Daddy), Ludacris, Flo Rida (whose stage name is a tribute to his home state, Florida), British-Jamaican hip-hop artist Stefflon Don (real name Stephanie Victoria Allen), LL Cool J, and Chingy.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Black metal artists also adopt pseudonyms, usually symbolizing dark values, such as Nocturno Culto, Gaahl, Abbath, and Silenoz.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] In punk and hardcore punk, singers and band members often replace real names with tougher-sounding stage names such as Sid Vicious of the late 1970s band Sex Pistols and "Rat" of the early 1980s band The Varukers and the 2000s re-formation of Discharge.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The punk rock band The Ramones had every member take the last name of Ramone.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Henry John Deutschendorf Jr., an American singer-songwriter, used the stage name John Denver.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] The Australian country musician born Robert Lane changed his name to Tex Morton.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonym] Reginald Kenneth Dwight legally changed his name in 1972 to Elton John.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization (or pseudonymisation, the spelling under European guidelines) is one way to comply with the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) demands for secure data storage of personal information.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data can be restored to its original state with the addition of information which allows individuals to be re-identified.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] In contrast, anonymization is intended to prevent re-identification of individuals within the dataset.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] The European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) on 9 December 2021 highlighted pseudonymization as the top technical supplementary measure for Schrems II compliance.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Less than two weeks later, the EU Commission highlighted pseudonymization as an essential element of the equivalency decision for South Korea, which is the status that was lost by the United States under the Schrems II ruling by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Protects against unauthorized re-identification via the mosaic effect by generating high entropy (uncertainty) levels by dynamically assigning different tokens at different times for various purposes.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Before the Schrems II ruling, pseudonymization was a technique used by security experts or government officials to hide personally identifiable information to maintain data structure and privacy of information.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Some common examples of sensitive information include postal code, location of individuals, names of individuals, race and gender, etc.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] After the Schrems II ruling, GDPR-compliant pseudonymization must satisfy the above-noted elements as an "outcome" versus merely a technique.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] The choice of which data fields are to be pseudonymized is partly subjective.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Less selective fields, such as birth date or postal code are often also included because they are usually available from other sources and therefore make a record easier to identify.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymizing these less identifying fields removes most of their analytic value and is therefore normally accompanied by the introduction of new derived and less identifying forms, such as year of birth or a larger postal code region.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Data fields that are less identifying, such as date of attendance, are usually not pseudonymized.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] This is because too much statistical utility is lost in doing so, not because the data cannot be identified.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] For example, given prior knowledge of a few attendance dates it is easy to identify someone's data in a pseudonymized dataset by selecting only those people with that pattern of dates.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] This is an example of an inference attack.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] The weakness of pre-GDPR pseudonymized data to inference attacks is commonly overlooked.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] A famous example is the AOL search data scandal.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] The pseudonym allows tracking back of data to its origins, which distinguishes pseudonymization from anonymization, where all person-related data that could allow backtracking has been purged.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization is an issue in, for example, patient-related data that has to be passed on securely between clinical centers.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] The application of pseudonymization to e-health intends to preserve the patient's privacy and data confidentiality.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] It allows primary use of medical records by authorized health care providers and privacy preserving secondary use by researchers.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] In the US, HIPAA provides guidelines on how health care data must be handled and data de-identification or pseudonymization is one way to simplify HIPAA compliance.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] However, plain pseudonymization for privacy preservation often reaches its limits when genetic data are involved (see also genetic privacy).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Due to the identifying nature of genetic data, depersonalization is often not sufficient to hide the corresponding person.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Potential solutions are the combination of pseudonymization with fragmentation and encryption.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Effective as of May 25, 2018, the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) defines pseudonymization for the very first time at the EU level in Article 4(5).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Under Article 4(5) definitional requirements, data is pseudonymized if it cannot be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of separately kept "additional information".
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data embodies the state of the art in Data Protection by Design and by Default because it requires protection of both direct and indirect identifiers (not just direct).
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Because access to separately kept "additional information" is required for re-identification, attribution of data to a specific data subject can be limited by the controller to support lawful purposes only.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] "...implement appropriate technical and organizational measures for ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] That obligation applies to the amount of personal data collected, the extent of their processing, the period of their storage and their accessibility.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] A central core of Data Protection by Design and by Default under GDPR Article 25 is enforcement of technology controls that support appropriate uses and the ability to keep promises.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] This trust cannot be maintained using outdated approaches to data protection.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization, as newly defined under the GDPR, is a means of helping to achieve Data Protection by Design and by Default to earn and maintain trust and more effectively serve businesses, researchers, healthcare providers, and everyone who relies on the integrity of data.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] GDPR-compliant pseudonymization not only enables greater privacy-respectful use of data in the "big data" world of data sharing and combining, but it also enables data controllers and processors to reap explicit benefits under the GDPR for correctly pseudonymized data.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Article 9(2)(j) with regard to overcoming the general prohibition on processing Article 9(1) special categories of personal data.
[src:pseudonymization/pseudonymization] Under Article 20(1), data controllers using Legitimate Interest processing are not subject to the right of portability, which applies only to consent-based processing.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system must be secured and validated using security best practices applicable to sensitive data protection, secure storage, audit, authentication and authorization.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system provides data processing applications with the authority and interfaces to request tokens, or detokenize back to sensitive data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The security and risk reduction benefits of tokenization require that the tokenization system is logically isolated and segmented from data processing systems and applications that previously processed or stored sensitive data replaced by tokens.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Only the tokenization system can tokenize data to create tokens, or detokenize back to redeem sensitive data under strict security controls.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The token generation method must be proven to have the property that there is no feasible means through direct attack, cryptanalysis, side channel analysis, token mapping table exposure or brute force techniques to reverse tokens back to live data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Replacing live data with tokens in systems is intended to minimize exposure of sensitive data to those applications, stores, people and processes, reducing risk of compromise or accidental exposure and unauthorized access to sensitive data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Applications can operate using tokens instead of live data, with the exception of a small number of trusted applications explicitly permitted to detokenize when strictly necessary for an approved business purpose.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems may be operated in-house within a secure isolated segment of the data center, or as a service from a secure service provider.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization may be used to safeguard sensitive data involving, for example, bank accounts, financial statements, medical records, criminal records, driver's licenses, loan applications, stock trades, voter registrations, and other types of personally identifiable information (PII).
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is often used in credit card processing.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council defines tokenization as "a process by which the primary account number (PAN) is replaced with a surrogate value called a token.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] A PAN may be linked to a reference number through the tokenization process.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In this case, the merchant simply has to retain the token and a reliable third party controls the relationship and holds the PAN.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The token may be created independently of the PAN, or the PAN can be used as part of the data input to the tokenization technique.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The communication between the merchant and the third-party supplier must be secure to prevent an attacker from intercepting to gain the PAN and the token.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] De-tokenization is the reverse process of redeeming a token for its associated PAN value.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The security of an individual token relies predominantly on the infeasibility of determining the original PAN knowing only the surrogate value".
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The choice of tokenization as an alternative to other techniques such as encryption will depend on varying regulatory requirements, interpretation, and acceptance by respective auditing or assessment entities.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This is in addition to any technical, architectural or operational constraint that tokenization imposes in practical use.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The concept of tokenization, as adopted by the industry today, has existed since the first currency systems emerged centuries ago as a means to reduce risk in handling high value financial instruments by replacing them with surrogate equivalents.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In the physical world, coin tokens have a long history of use replacing the financial instrument of minted coins and banknotes.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In more recent history, subway tokens and casino chips found adoption for their respective systems to replace physical currency and cash handling risks such as theft.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Exonumia and scrip are terms synonymous with such tokens.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In the digital world, similar substitution techniques have been used since the 1970s as a means to isolate real data elements from exposure to other data systems.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In databases for example, surrogate key values have been used since 1976 to isolate data associated with the internal mechanisms of databases and their external equivalents for a variety of uses in data processing.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] More recently, these concepts have been extended to consider this isolation tactic to provide a security mechanism for the purposes of data protection.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In the payment card industry, tokenization is one means of protecting sensitive cardholder data in order to comply with industry standards and government regulations.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization was applied to payment card data by Shift4 Corporation and released to the public during an industry Security Summit in Las Vegas, Nevada in 2005.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The technology is meant to prevent the theft of the credit card information in storage.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Shift4 defines tokenization as: "The concept of using a non-decryptable piece of data to represent, by reference, sensitive or secret data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] To protect data over its full lifecycle, tokenization is often combined with end-to-end encryption to secure data in transit to the tokenization system or service, with a token replacing the original data on return.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] For example, to avoid the risks of malware stealing data from low-trust systems such as point of sale (POS) systems, as in the Target breach of 2013, cardholder data encryption must take place prior to card data entering the POS and not after.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also specified end-to-end encryption (certified point-to-point encryption—P2PE) for various service implementations in various PCI Council Point-to-point Encryption documents.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems share several components according to established standards.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Token mapping – this is the process of assigning the created token value to its original value.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] To enable permitted look-ups of the original value using the token as the index, a secure cross-reference database must be constructed.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Token data store – this is a central repository for the token mapping process that holds the original sensitive values and their related token values.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Sensitive data and token values must be securely kept in an encrypted format.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Strong key management procedures are required for sensitive data encryption on token data stores.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization and "classic" encryption effectively protect data if implemented properly, and a computer security system may use both.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] While similar in certain regards, tokenization and classic encryption differ in a few key aspects.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Both are cryptographic data security methods and they essentially have the same function, however they do so with differing processes and have different effects on the data they are protecting.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes without altering the type or length of data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This is an important distinction from encryption because changes in data length and type can render information unreadable in intermediate systems such as databases.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenized data can still be processed by legacy systems which makes tokenization more flexible than classic encryption.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In many situations, the encryption process is a constant consumer of processing power, hence such a system needs significant expenditures in specialized hardware and software.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Another difference is that tokens require significantly less computational resources to process.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] With tokenization, specific data is kept fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This allows tokenized data to be processed more quickly and reduces the strain on system resources.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This can be a key advantage in systems that rely on high performance.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In comparison to encryption, tokenization technologies reduce time, expense, and administrative effort while enabling teamwork and communication.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] There are many ways that tokens can be classified.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] However, there is currently no unified classification.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be single or multi-use, cryptographic or non-cryptographic, reversible or irreversible, authenticable or non-authenticable, and various combinations thereof.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In the context of payments, the difference between high and low value tokens plays a significant role.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] High-value tokens (HVT) serve as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions and are used as an instrument for completing a payment transaction.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In order to function, they must look like actual PANs.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Multiple HVT can map back to a single PAN and a single physical credit card without the owner being aware of it.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Additionally, HVT can be limited to certain networks and/or merchants whereas PANs cannot.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] HVT can also be bound to specific devices so that anomalies between token use, physical devices, and geographic locations can be flagged as potentially fraudulent.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] HVT blocking enhances efficiency by reducing computational costs while maintaining accuracy and reducing record linkage as it reduces the number of records that are compared.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Low-value tokens (LVT) also act as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions, however they serve a different purpose.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] LVT cannot be used by themselves to complete a payment transaction.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In order for an LVT to function, it must be possible to match it back to the actual PAN it represents, albeit only in a tightly controlled fashion.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Using tokens to protect PANs becomes ineffectual if a tokenization system is breached, therefore securing the tokenization system itself is extremely important.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] First generation tokenization systems use a database to map from live data to surrogate substitute tokens and back.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This requires the storage, management, and continuous backup for every new transaction added to the token database to avoid data loss.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Another problem is ensuring consistency across data centers, requiring continuous synchronization of token databases.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Significant consistency, availability and performance trade-offs, per the CAP theorem, are unavoidable with this approach.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This overhead adds complexity to real-time transaction processing to avoid data loss and to assure data integrity across data centers, and also limits scale.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Storing all sensitive data in one service creates an attractive target for attack and compromise, and introduces privacy and legal risk in the aggregation of data Internet privacy, particularly in the EU.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Another limitation of tokenization technologies is measuring the level of security for a given solution through independent validation.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] With the lack of standards, the latter is critical to establish the strength of tokenization offered when tokens are used for regulatory compliance.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The method of generating tokens may also have limitations from a security perspective.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] With concerns about security and attacks to random number generators, which are a common choice for the generation of tokens and token mapping tables, scrutiny must be applied to ensure proven and validated methods are used versus arbitrary design.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Random-number generators have limitations in terms of speed, entropy, seeding and bias, and security properties must be carefully analysed and measured to avoid predictability and compromise.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Stateless tokenization allows live data elements to be mapped to surrogate values randomly, without relying on a database, while maintaining the isolation properties of tokenization.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] November 2014, American Express released its token service which meets the EMV tokenization standard.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Other notable examples of tokenization-based payment systems, according to the EMVCo standard, include Google Wallet, Apple Pay, Samsung Pay, Microsoft Wallet, Fitbit Pay and Garmin Pay.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Visa uses tokenization techniques to provide a secure online and mobile shopping.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Using blockchain, as opposed to relying on trusted third parties, it is possible to run highly accessible, tamper-resistant databases for transactions.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] With help of blockchain, tokenization is the process of converting the value of a tangible or intangible asset into a token that can be exchanged on the network.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This enables the tokenization of conventional financial assets, for instance, by transforming rights into a digital token backed by the asset itself using blockchain technology.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Besides that, tokenization enables the simple and efficient compartmentalization and management of data across multiple users.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Individual tokens created through tokenization can be used to split ownership and partially resell an asset.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Consequently, only entities with the appropriate token can access the data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Numerous blockchain companies support asset tokenization.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In 2019, eToro acquired Firmo and renamed as eToroX.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Through its Token Management Suite, which is backed by USD-pegged stablecoins, eToroX enables asset tokenization.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization of equity is facilitated by STOKR, a platform that links investors with small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokens issued through the STOKR platform are legally recognized as transferable securities under European Union capital market regulations.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Breakers enable tokenization of intellectual property, allowing content creators to issue their own digital tokens.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be distributed to a variety of project participants.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Without intermediaries or governing body, content creators can integrate reward-sharing features into the token.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Building an alternate payments system requires a number of entities working together in order to deliver near field communication (NFC) or other technology based payment services to the end users.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] One of the issues is the interoperability between the players and to resolve this issue the role of trusted service manager (TSM) is proposed to establish a technical link between mobile network operators (MNO) and providers of services, so that these entities can work together.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can play a role in mediating such services.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization as a security strategy lies in the ability to replace a real card number with a surrogate (target removal) and the subsequent limitations placed on the surrogate card number (risk reduction).
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] If the surrogate value can be used in an unlimited fashion or even in a broadly applicable manner, the token value gains as much value as the real credit card number.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In these cases, the token may be secured by a second dynamic token that is unique for each transaction and also associated to a specific payment card.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Example of dynamic, transaction-specific tokens include cryptograms used in the EMV (Europay, Mastercard, and Visa) specification.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, an industry-wide set of guidelines that must be met by any organization that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data, mandates that credit card data must be protected when stored.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization, as applied to payment card data, is often implemented to meet this mandate, replacing credit card and automated clearing house (ACH) numbers in some systems with a random value or string of characters.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be formatted in a variety of ways.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Some token service providers or tokenization products generate the surrogate values in such a way as to match the format of the original sensitive data.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In the case of payment card data, a token might be the same length as a primary account number (bank card number) and contain elements of the original data such as the last four digits of the card number.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] When a payment card authorization request is made to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, a token might be returned to the merchant instead of the card number, along with the authorization code for the transaction.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The token is stored in the receiving system while the actual cardholder data is mapped to the token in a secure tokenization system.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Storage of tokens and payment card data must comply with current PCI standards, including the use of strong cryptography.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is currently in standards definition in ANSI X9 as X9.119 Part 2.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] X9 is responsible for the industry standards for financial cryptography and data protection including payment card PIN management, credit and debit card encryption and related technologies and processes.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also stated support for tokenization in reducing risk in data breaches, when combined with other technologies such as Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) and assessments of compliance to PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Visa Inc. released Visa Tokenization Best Practices for tokenization uses in credit and debit card handling applications and services.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] In March 2014, EMVCo LLC released its first payment tokenization specification for EMV.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] PCI DSS is the most frequently utilized standard for Tokenization systems used by payment industry players.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can render it more difficult for attackers to gain access to sensitive data outside of the tokenization system or service.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Implementation of tokenization may simplify the requirements of the PCI DSS, as systems that no longer store or process sensitive data may have a reduction of applicable controls required by the PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] This validation is particularly important in tokenization, as the tokens are shared externally in general use and thus exposed in high risk, low trust environments.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] The infeasibility of reversing a token or set of tokens to a live sensitive data must be established using industry accepted measurements and proofs by appropriate experts independent of the service or solution provider.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Not all organizational data can be tokenized, and needs to be examined and filtered.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] When databases are utilized on a large scale, they expand exponentially, causing the search process to take longer, restricting system performance, and increasing backup processes.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] A database that links sensitive information to tokens is called a vault.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] With the addition of new data, the vault's maintenance workload increases significantly.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] For ensuring database consistency, token databases need to be continuously synchronized.
[src:pseudonymization/tokenization-data-security] Apart from that, secure communication channels must be built between sensitive data and the vault so that data is not compromised on the way to or from storage.
